## Migration: `EventProcessor` → .NET 8

### Problems in the original code

| API | Issue on .NET 8 |
|-----|-----------------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` (SYSLIB0006) |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | Obsolete (SYSLIB0046 in .NET 9); unreliable for `WaitOne` wakeup |
| `ManualResetEvent.WaitOne()` | Not cancellation-aware — can't be woken cooperatively |

### Pattern classification

- **`RunLoop` with `WaitOne`** → Blocking call interruption
- **`Stop()` with `Interrupt`/`Abort`** → Cancellable work loop

### Migrated code

```csharp
using System.Threading.Channels;

public class EventProcessor
{
    private readonly Channel<string> _channel = Channel.CreateUnbounded<string>();
    private Task? _runTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _runTask = Task.Run(() => RunLoopAsync(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task RunLoopAsync(CancellationToken token)
    {
        await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(token))
        {
            Handle(item);
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        _channel.Writer.TryWrite(item);
    }

    public async Task StopAsync()
    {
        _channel.Writer.Complete();          // signals no more items
        _cts?.Cancel();                      // wakes blocked ReadAsync
        if (_runTask is not null)
            await _runTask.WaitAsync(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* ... */ }
}
```

### Key changes explained

1. **`Channel<T>` replaces `Queue` + `ManualResetEvent` + `lock`** — thread-safe, async-ready producer/consumer with built-in backpressure.
2. **`CancellationToken` replaces `Thread.Interrupt`/`Abort`** — `ReadAllAsync` checks the token cooperatively.
3. **`Task.Run` replaces `new Thread`** — uses the thread pool; `async Task` enables awaitable shutdown.
4. **`StopAsync` is graceful** — completing the writer drains remaining items, then cancellation breaks out if still blocked.

### Pitfalls to watch for

| Pitfall | Mitigation |
|---------|------------|
| `Handle()` is long-running and ignores cancellation | Pass `token` into `Handle` and check `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at checkpoints |
| Forgetting to dispose `CancellationTokenSource` | Always dispose in `StopAsync` or via `IAsyncDisposable` |
| Calling `Enqueue` after `Stop` | `TryWrite` returns `false` after `Complete()`—check it or throw |
| Lost items on cancellation | `Cancel()` aborts mid-read; if you need to drain, await without cancelling and rely on `Complete()` alone |

### If you need synchronous `Stop()` (no async caller)

```csharp
public void Stop()
{
    _channel.Writer.Complete();
    _cts?.Cancel();
    try { _runTask?.Wait(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5)); }
    catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerException is OperationCanceledException) { }
    _cts?.Dispose();
}
```

This eliminates all `Thread.Abort`, `Thread.Interrupt`, and manual synchronization while preserving the same queue-processing semantics.
